text: The clergy of the Great Orthodoxy and its cults to Kislev’s holy pantheon, of which Ursun is the most prominent.
Often found amongst the nobility or in the more salacious districts, the Dark Prince’s cults feed on desire and excess.

Isabella was on her deathbed before Vlad finally turned her with the Blood Kiss, realising that he could not carry on without her. Since then, they have forever been at each other’s side – in both tireless love and eternal Undeath.
Masters are Dreadlords in the making. They are yet to prove themselves in command of their own raiding party, but are eager to show their abilities and deadly ambition.
To be in the Warlord’s cadre, scheming must come as naturally as breathing, for it takes a great leader to speak great lies.
Vampire Fleet Captains are spellcasters and the masters of the crew, punishing all disobedience with a severe lashing.
The brightest, most luminous and fluxon of Horrors – both gibbering fool and savant. Such is the power of Change.
Liche Priests are the undying members of the Nehekhara's Mortuary Cult, and they hold the secrets to Unlife.
Tomb Princes are the sons of the Tomb Kings. Each of the kings of ancient Nehekhara had many heirs, but only one could succeed his father to the throne.
The clergy of the Great Orthodoxy and its cults to Kislev’s holy pantheon, of which Ursun is the most prominent.
An ancient, intrinsically evil race of amphibians, the Fimir worshipped the Ruinous Powers long before the fickle Gods’ attentions were drawn by man’s endless potential.
Battle Wizards are strange figures who wield awesome magical powers and are privy to secrets beyond the ken of normal folk.
An ancient, intrinsically evil race of amphibians, the Fimir worshipped the Ruinous Powers long before the fickle Gods’ attentions were drawn by man’s endless potential.
Loners, and fierce Ogre Warriors who excel at tracking prey, especially the large fauna of the mountain tribes.
Fearsome creatures of the night; the very stuff of nightmares. Mourngul Haunters strike fear into the hearts of their helpless prey.
Tainted from before birth, there is a beast inside each and every Skin Wolf, waiting to be unleashed by unspeakably dark rituals afore the Gods.
The Astromancers of Cathay were taught magic by the Dragons at the Celestial Court.
The most expressive, or perhaps depraved, of Slaanesh’s Daemonettes, able to seduce any mortal with a mere wanton glare.
Victims of plague who pray to Nurgle for mercy will often fall under his sway, never released from their infection and doomed to spread it further.
Dedicating their lives to the Fire Mouth, they are prophets of the volcano – eager to eat and burn.
Butchers are emissaries of the Great Maw, preparers of the feasts and wielders of gut-magic.
Captains have risen through the ranks, having first stood amongst the rank and file with a bloody halberd in their hands.
Younger initiates to the Ice Court, blessed with magical abilities and tutored in the Lores of Ice and Tempest.
Younger initiates to the Ice Court, blessed with magical abilities and tutored in the Lores of Ice and Tempest.
The future is written for those with the knowledge to read it.
Infiltrating enemy battle lines and sowing disruption in their wake, a Glade Captain’s initiative enables them to strike opportunistic blows.

Chaos Cultists are gradually consumed by the Dark Gods’ insidious corruption, finding their resolve siphoned away, causing them to turn against everything they once loved. Such beings live behind a veneer of respectability, silently working to ensure the rise of Ruin and Destruction.
Necrotects are architects of extraordinary skill whose ambitions far outpace what can be achieved in a mortal lifespan.
Outcast elemental Wizards find refuge in the House of Secrets where they excel in arcane metallurgy.

Masters of the ballistic arts, even in death Gunnery Wights maintain the lines and a steady flow of black powder.
Not mere courtiers as the name suggests, but awe-inspiring warriors and envoys of the Everqueen, who speak with her authority in all matters.
Cultists of Khorne are found in gladiatorial pits and other fighting arenas where blood is spilt for sport and profit.
Those champions of Chaos who seek mastery over the magical arts are known as Chaos Sorcerers; they are madmen and malcontents all.
The most prominent of Nurgle’s tallymen, the Plagueridden will count every affliction brought upon the mortal realms.
This fallen Paladin is cursed to 'live', forever damned, at Cylostra's side. He doesn't even like music…
Specially trained to deliver lashing pain, Packmasters excel at hurting their enemies while simultaneously goading their hulking monstrosities to do the same.
Those champions of Chaos who seek mastery over the magical arts are known as Chaos Sorcerers; they are madmen and malcontents all.
As valued members of their Lord’s entourage, Shaman-Sorcerers read the portents from sacrificial entrails and flickering fires to divine a glimpse of events yet to come.
The history of many Exalted Heroes, recorded in scattered chronicles by the free people of the Old World, is a catalogue of woes and evil deeds.
Wargors are feared and respected as brutal Champions with no regard for any concerns of the tribe other than battle.
The most prominent of Nurgle’s tallymen, the Plagueridden will count every affliction brought upon the mortal realms.
The most expressive, or perhaps depraved, of Slaanesh’s Daemonettes, able to seduce any mortal with a mere wanton glare.
Captains have risen through the ranks, having first stood amongst the rank and file with a bloody halberd in their hands.
Judge, jury and executioner combined, a Witch Hunter will use any means necessary to burn heresy from the heart of the Empire.
The prayer of a Warrior Priest is a call to war, their hymns the clash of arms and their benedictions are the smiting of Sigmar's foes.
Underhanded ploys and strategy are the preferred tactics for Goblin Big Bosses. Although fighting is still an option, it is one that is typically left to the especially desperate.
Wight Kings are incredibly powerful Undead, almost as hard to destroy as Vampires. Suffused with Dark Magic, their weapons shimmer with baleful energy.
A single Banshee is a terrifying prospect, and even those warriors skilled enough to match blades with a Vampire have little defence against her unnatural screams.
Vampires are the true masters of Undeath. Despite their curse, Vampires retain all of their devious intelligence, and hence all of their ambition and desire.
The history of many Exalted Heroes, recorded in scattered chronicles by the free people of the Old World, is a catalogue of woes and evil deeds.
As well as leading bands of Nagarythe’s most deadly killers, the Hand of the Shadow Crown excels at lone missions, be they sabotage or assassination.
Thanes are the most powerful fighters in the army, fell-handed warriors equipped with the finest arms and armour of the Clan's weapon hoard.
A Paladin's reputation precedes them, and their names and heraldry are known throughout all the dukedoms.
The history of many Exalted Heroes, recorded in scattered chronicles by the free people of the Old World, is a catalogue of woes and evil deeds.
The brightest, most luminous and fluxon of Horrors – both gibbering fool and savant. Such is the power of Change.
Runesmiths work spells with their hammercraft, binding the Winds of Magic into mighty runes of power.
Master Engineers are doughty warriors, and while they might be more interested in drafting plans for fortifications, they are more than capable of fighting in the front lines.
Battle Wizards are strange figures who wield awesome magical powers and are privy to secrets beyond the ken of normal folk.
Damsels are powerful individuals, for in their years away from Bretonnia, their innate abilities have been honed and tempered.
Those champions of Chaos who seek mastery over the magical arts are known as Chaos Sorcerers; they are madmen and malcontents all.
Bloodreapers are the first to grasp the freshly-forged Hellblades; as the most eager to spill blood, they become Khorne’s chosen.
A Shaman is a living conduit to Gork and Mork and can wield such arcane might that even the crustiest old Warbosses have to be impressed.
Necromancers are amongst the most cursed of all those who practice the magical arts, for they have exchanged their humanity for the ability to raise the dead.
Bray-Shamans are vile to behold, their filthy bodies covered in matted fur into which all manner of crude fetishes and grim charms are woven.
Gorebulls are the strongest and most ferocious of their kind, towering bull-headed and cloven-hoofed beasts almost as broad as they are tall.
The Spellsingers of Athel Loren shield themselves by joining their minds to the forest's sleeping consciousness.
A Waystalker can pick out a single enemy from a seething mass of troops and place the one perfect shot that brings the target, lifeless, to the ground.
The Death Hags are the priestesses of the Witch Elves, the guardians of Khaine's mysteries.
Khainite Assassins are masters of a subtle and murderous magic, trained from infancy to be the chosen warriors of the Bloody-handed God.
Sorceresses study the magic art, utterly seduced by the unrestrained energy it allows them to command.
Loremasters are invariable gifted warriors. Similarly, each has a faultless grasp of the principles of magical lore.
It is by Mages' efforts that the Great Vortex and the network of Waystones that feed it are maintained; the dread power of Chaos is thus kept in abeyance.
Branchwraiths have long served as the handmaidens to the Ancients of Athel Loren, and attend to the Treemen with a dedication bordering on the fanatical.
Warlock Engineers are the artificers of Skaven society, blending arcane sorceries with technology in an insane and mind-boggling mix.
Black Orcs don’t often fight solo, but their obsession with killing things means some willingly end up as one-Orc armies.
Plague Priests and Eshin Sorcerers lead their foul brethren in the creation of new and virulent diseases, or support them with through their command of the sneakiest of arts: that of stealth.
Skink Chiefs are Skinks who have been marked for greatness. It is they who typically oversee patrols and major construction projects.
Skink Priests can channel the forces of nature to aid their cause, or unleash eldritch energies to smite their enemies.
Saurus Scar-Veterans are perfectly designed killing machines, their martial prowess further enhanced by battle experience.
Glistening with putrid swamp gunk, Troll Hags sate their voracious appetites with anything and everything they can get their slimy hands on.
The noble families of Ulthuan have led the High Elves through times of peace and conflict for thousands of years.
Skaven Assassins are elite killers in a class of their own. The art of sabotage, arson, and poison all form part of their deadly bag of tricks.
Bloodreapers are the first to grasp the freshly-forged Hellblades; as the most eager to spill blood, they become Khorne’s chosen.
Cultists of Tzeentch are drawn to sanctums of knowledge, secret societies, libraries and repositories of lost lore.
